285ctt-0002ctt-0002.xmlCubical Type TheoryDefinition2024823Trey Plante
Cubical type theory is a constructive approach to homotopy type theory..270ctt-0004ctt-0004.xmlCofibration LogicsDefinition202494Trey Plante
A cofibration logic is a first-order intuitonstic logic used in the definition of cubical type theories.
    Like any first-order logic, a cofibration logic is defined by a description of terms and formulas.
The terms of a cofibration logic are a specification of the structure of \mathbb {I}, the interval.
    The simplest interval term structure contains the endpoints 0 and 1 and arbitrary variables x_i.
    The most complex interval term structure contains the above and joins, meets, and complements (DeMorgan Algebra).
    In cubical type thoeries, the specified structure of \mathbb {I} is used to reason about the dimensions of the n-cube.
    Varying term definitions lead to varying levels of complexity of the path structure in a cubical type theory.
The formulas of a cofibration logic are a fragment of intuitionistic first-order equational logic over interval terms.
    The formulas of a cofibration logic are called cofibrations. Cofibrations are used in cubical type theory to reason
    about portions of paths.272ctt-0001ctt-0001.xmlPartial ElementsDefinition2024823Trey Plante
Partial elements are elements of a type that are defined on the extent of a cofibration formula. Partial elements are used in cubical type theory
to describe partially specified n-dimensional cubes.
I use the notation  [\alpha ] \rightarrow  A  for the type
of partial elements of A defined on  \alpha  .  Partial elements internalize the structure of the judgement  \alpha  \vdash  a : A.
The typing rules for partial elements are as follows:
