274ctt-0003ctt-0003.xmlBoundary TypesDefinition2024828Trey Plante
A boundary type is a type that describes the witness of a partial element being ``extensible''.
  Given a partial element u : [\alpha ] \to  A, the boundary type A[\alpha  \to  u] is the type of elements a : A that ``extend'' u. A term a : A[\alpha  \to  u] is a proof that a : A and u : A agree on \alpha .
  Any term u : A is a term of A[\alpha  \to  u] because u is equivalent with itself. Thus, the boundary type internalizes two judgments: \Gamma  \vdash  a : A and \Gamma , \alpha  \vdash  a \equiv  u : A.
  Boundary types can be thought of as a \Sigma -type: \Sigma  (a : A) ([\phi ] \to  A \equiv  u).
