287mlg-0001mlg-0001.xmlNotes on Mathematical Logic202493Trey Plante
These are notes from a Mathematical Logic class taught by
    Alexander Van Abel at Wesleyan University. Any mistakes in the
    following material are my own.234mlg-0002mlg-0002.xmlFirst-order LanguageDefinition202493
A first-order language \mathcal {L} is an infinite collection of distinct symbols,
where no symbol is contained in another, in the following categories:

The following are logical symbols that belong to every language:

"(", ")"


"\lor ", "\lnot "


"\forall "


"v_1," "v_{2}", ... (an infinite sequence of variables). The set of variables is denoted
        Vars.


"="


The following are non-logical symbols that a language is not required to contain

Constant symbols.


For every n, n-ary function symbols.


For every n, n-ary relation symbols.235mlg-0003mlg-0003.xmlTerm of a LanguageDefinition202493Trey Plante
If \mathcal {L} is a language a term of \mathcal {L} is a nonempty finite string t of symbols
from \mathcal {L} such that either:

t is a constant symbol


t is a variable


t \coloneq  f t_{1} t_{2} \cdots  t_{n}, , where f is an n-ary function symbol of
        \mathcal {L} and each of the t_i is a term of \mathcal {L}


The set of terms of \mathcal {L} is the smallest set of strings that adhere to the preceding properties.


The symbol \coloneq  is not a part of \mathcal {L}, but a meta-linguistic symbol that means
    the strings of \mathcal {L}-symbols on each side of the \coloneq  are identical.237mlg-0004mlg-0004.xmlFormula of a languageDefinition202495Trey Plante
If \mathcal {L} is a first-order language, a formula of \mathcal {L} is a nonempty
    finite string \phi  of symbols from \mathcal {L} such that either:

\phi  :\equiv  = t_{1}t_{2}, where t_{1} and t_{2} are terms of \mathcal {L}


\phi  :\equiv  R t_{1}t_{2}\cdots  t_{n}, where R is an n-ary relation symbol of
            \mathcal {L} and t_{1}, \cdots , t_{n} are all terms of \mathcal {L}


\phi  :\equiv  (\lnot  \alpha ), where \alpha  is a formula of \mathcal {L}


\phi  :\equiv  (\alpha  \lor  \beta ), where \alpha  and \beta  are formulas of \mathcal {L}


\phi  :\equiv  (\forall  v)(\alpha ), where v is a variable and \alpha  is a formula of \mathcal {L}
The set of formulas of \mathcal {L} is the smallest set of strings that adhere to the preceding properties.239mlg-0006mlg-0006.xmlLanguage of Number TheoryDefinition202499Trey Plante
The language \mathcal {L}_{NT} is \{0, S, +, \cdot , E, <\} , where 0
   is a constant symbol, S is a unary function symbol, +, \cdot , and E
   are binary function symbols, and < is a binary relation symbol. This will be referred to
   as the language of number theory.241mlg-0005mlg-0005.xmlFree variableDefinition202499
Suppose that v is a variable and \phi  is a formula. We will say that
    v is free in \phi  if

\phi  is atomic and v and occurs in \phi 

\phi  :\equiv  (\lnot  \alpha ) and v is free in \alpha 

\phi  :\equiv  (\alpha  \lor  \beta ) and v is free in at least one of \alpha  or \beta 

\phi  :\equiv  (\forall  u)(\alpha ) and v is not u and v is free \alpha 242mlg-0007mlg-0007.xml\mathcal {L}-structureDefinition202499
Fix a language \mathcal {L}. A \mathcal {L}-structure \mathcal {U} is a nonempty
   set A, called the universe of \mathcal {U}, together with:

For each constant symbol c of \mathcal {L}, an element u^{\mathcal {U}} of \mathcal {A}

For each n-ary function symbol f of \mathcal {L}, a function f^{\mathcal {U}} : A^{n} \to  A

For each n-ary relation symbol R of \mathcal {L}, an n-ary relation R^{\mathcal {U}} on A, or a R^{\mathcal {U}} \subset  A^{n}
For example, consider \mathcal {N} = (\mathbb {N}, 0, S, +, \cdot , E, <), where we ignore
    the superscripts for the constants, functions, and relations and everything else gets its standard
    interpretation. This structure is called the standard \mathcal {L}^{NT}-structure.


289hott-0004hott-0004.xmlNotes on Homotopy Type Theory202494Trey Plante261hott-0003hott-0003.xml\Pi (S^{1}) = \mathbb {Z} Theorem202494Trey Plante257hott-0002hott-0002.xmlApLemma202494Trey Plante
Suppose that f : A \to  B is a function. Then for any x, y : A there is an operation
    ap_{f} : (x =_{A} y) \to  (f(x) =_{B} f(y)).
Moreover, for each x : A we have ap_{f}(refl_{x}) \equiv  refl_{f(x)}
The notation ap_{f} can be read as the application of f to a path, or as the action
    on paths of f.
It suffices (by induction) to define ap_{f}(refl) :\equiv  refl_{f(x)} : f(x) = f(x)
